      <biogHist>
        <abstract>
          An Italian-language course was offered by the Department of French from 1893 until
            1926. In 1926, the Department of Italian was established. In 1939, the Department of
            French and the Department of Italian were combined to form the Department of French and
            Other Romance Languages, which also offered courses in Spanish and Portuguese.
        </abstract>
        <p>Before the creation of the Department of Italian in 1926, an Italian-language course was
          offered by the Department of French, which had been established in 1893. Students were
          required to have completed two years of French in order to take Italian. The course was
          offered every two years, alternating with a Spanish course. In 1926, a separate Department
          of Italian was listed among the Departments of Instruction. In 1939, the Department of
          French and the Department of Italian were combined to form the Department of French and
          Other Romance Languages, which also offered courses in Spanish and Portuguese.</p>
      </biogHist>

    </description>

